1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,651
Ever ask yourself, what is my greatest weakness?

2
00:00:03,920 --> 00:00:10,131
Probably the greatest human weakness is self-deprecation, that is, selling oneself short.

3
00:00:10,480 --> 00:00:13,971
Self-deprecation shows through in countless ways.

4
00:00:14,321 --> 00:00:17,251
John sees a job advertisement in the paper.

5
00:00:17,280 --> 00:00:19,330
It's exactly what he would like.

6
00:00:19,520 --> 00:00:25,251
But he does nothing about it because he thinks, I'm not good enough for that job, so why bother?

7
00:00:25,601 --> 00:00:31,971
Or Jim wants a date with Joan, but he doesn't call her because he thinks he wouldn't rate with her.

8
00:00:32,560 --> 00:00:38,851
Tom feels Mr. Richards would be a very good prospect for his product, but Tom doesn't call.

9
00:00:39,040 --> 00:00:42,290
He feels Mr. Richards is too big to see him.

10
00:00:42,800 --> 00:00:45,971
Pete is filling out a job application form.

11
00:00:46,161 --> 00:00:50,211
One question asks, what beginning salary do you expect?

12
00:00:50,560 --> 00:00:57,571
Pete puts down a modest figure because he feels he really isn't worth the bigger sum he would like to earn.

13
00:00:58,161 --> 00:01:03,491
Philosophers for thousands of years have issued good advice, know thyself.

14
00:01:03,840 --> 00:01:10,371
But most people, it seems, interpret this suggestion to mean know only thy negative self.

15
00:01:10,721 --> 00:01:18,450
Most self-evaluation consists of making long mental lists of one's faults, shortcomings, inadequacies.

16
00:01:18,960 --> 00:01:24,290
It's well to know our inabilities, for this shows us areas in which we can improve.

17
00:01:24,560 --> 00:01:28,931
But if we know only our negative characteristics, we're in a mess.

18
00:01:29,040 --> 00:01:30,771
Our value is small.

19
00:01:31,200 --> 00:01:35,010
Here is an exercise to help you measure your true size.

20
00:01:35,280 --> 00:01:39,651
I've used it in training programs for executives and sales personnel.

21
00:01:39,760 --> 00:01:40,691
It works.

22
00:01:40,691 --> 00:01:42,131
1.

23
00:01:42,640 --> 00:01:45,170
Determine your five chief assets.

24
00:01:45,520 --> 00:01:51,411
Invite some objective friend to help, possibly your wife, your superior, a professor,

25
00:01:51,600 --> 00:01:55,251
some intelligent person who will give you an honest opinion.

26
00:01:55,520 --> 00:02:07,171
Examples of assets frequently listed are education, experience, technical skills, appearance, well-adjusted home life, attitudes, personality, initiative.

27
00:02:07,171 --> 00:02:08,770
2.

28
00:02:09,121 --> 00:02:20,450
Next, under each asset, write the names of three persons you know who have achieved large success but who do not have this asset to as great a degree as you.

29
00:02:21,200 --> 00:02:28,691
When you've completed this exercise, you will find you outrank many successful people on at least one asset.

30
00:02:29,121 --> 00:02:32,450
There is only one conclusion you can honestly reach.

31
00:02:32,640 --> 00:02:34,530
You're bigger than you think.

32
00:02:34,801 --> 00:02:37,571
So fit your thinking to your true size.

33
00:02:37,840 --> 00:02:40,131
Think as big as you really are.

34
00:02:40,480 --> 00:02:43,971
Never, never, never sell yourself short.

